-- Flower education data for tulips
-- Simple format: education_section and descriptions

INSERT INTO flower_education (education_section, descriptions) VALUES

('Introduction to Tulips', 
'Tulips are spring-blooming perennial plants known for their vibrant colors and elegant shape. They are one of the most popular flowers worldwide and come in a variety of colors including red, yellow, pink, white, purple, and orange. Tulips belong to the genus Tulipa and grow from bulbs. They typically bloom once per year in the spring. Plant tulip bulbs in the fall, 6-8 weeks before the ground freezes. Choose a location with well-draining soil and full to partial sunlight. Plant bulbs 6-8 inches deep with the pointed end facing up. Water thoroughly after planting and during dry periods in spring. After flowering, allow leaves to die back naturally. Tulips prefer cool climates and need a cold period to bloom properly.'),

('Tulip Colors and Their Meanings',
'Tulips come in many colors and each color has its own meaning. Red tulips represent true love and passion. Yellow tulips symbolize cheerful thoughts and friendship. Pink tulips convey caring and good wishes. White tulips represent forgiveness and purity. Purple tulips symbolize royalty and admiration. Orange tulips express enthusiasm and energy. Understanding tulip color meanings helps you choose the right tulips for any occasion. All tulip colors require the same basic care. Plant in well-draining soil with adequate sunlight. Water regularly during growing season but avoid overwatering. Different colored tulips do not require different care - their color is determined by genetics, not growing conditions.'),

('History and Origin of Tulips',
'Tulips have a long history that spans centuries. They were originally wildflowers in the mountains of Central Asia, in what is now modern-day Turkey and Iran. Early cultivation began in the Ottoman Empire around 1000 AD, where they became highly valued. The name tulip comes from the Turkish word meaning turban, due to the flowers shape. European cultivation began in the 16th century when Austrian ambassador Ogier de Busbecq introduced them from Constantinople. The Netherlands became the center of tulip cultivation, leading to Tulip Mania in the 1630s when bulbs sold for very high prices. Today, the Netherlands remains the worlds largest producer of tulip bulbs, exporting millions annually.'),

('How to Plant and Grow Tulips',
'To grow tulips successfully, plant bulbs in the fall, about 6-8 weeks before the first hard frost. Choose a sunny location with well-draining soil. Prepare the soil by removing weeds and adding compost if needed. Plant bulbs 6-8 inches deep with pointed end up, spacing them 4-6 inches apart. Water thoroughly after planting. In spring, water regularly when soil is dry. Apply a balanced fertilizer when shoots appear and again after flowering. Deadhead spent flowers but leave foliage until it yellows. In warmer climates, you may need to dig up bulbs after foliage dies and refrigerate for 8-12 weeks before replanting. For container planting, use deep pots with drainage holes and well-draining potting mix.');
